["Daily From print surrogate: \"el Nuevo Herald, una subsidiaria de The McClatchy Company.\" In Spanish, with Haitian Creole and Portuguese in some Sunday editions. Search engine available in both English and Spanish. Spanish language edition of: Miami herald (Miami, Fla. : 1910). Septiembre 10, 2019; title from caption (elnuevoherald.com, viewed September 10, 2019) Septiembre 10, 2019 (viewed September 10, 2019)."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-05-19T21:36:04.829Z", "group": ["ndnp/newspapers", "catalog-split-08", "catalog", "united-states-newspaper-directory", "main-catalog-split-08"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/2019201720/", "image_url": [], "index": 10, "language": ["portuguese", "creoles and pidgins, french-based", "spanish"], "location": ["dade county", "miami", "united states", "florida", "dade"], "number": ["2019201720", "42269974", "2688-8793", "online resource", "2025-07-01t13:41:06.800000", "2026-04-13t21:30:13"], "original_format": ["newspaper"], "partof": ["directory of u.s. newspapers in american libraries", "catalog", "el nuevo herald (miami, fla.;[miami, fl]) 19??-current [online resource]", "serial and government publications division"], "publication_frequency": ["daily"], "score": 66.383484, "shelf_id": "Newspaper F319.M6 N84", "site": ["usnd", "catalog"], "subject": ["dade", "newspapers", "latin american", "miami-dade county", "miami-dade county (fla.)", "hispanic americans", "spanish language materials", "miami", "electronic journals", "united states", "florida", "miami (fla.)"], "timestamp": "2026-05-26T20:57:39.303Z", "title": "El nuevo herald", "type": ["title"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/2019201720/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/item/2019201725/", "http://lccn.loc.gov/2019201725", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/86ededde-7358-5631-8045-c14c58aa0814"], "campaigns": [], "date": "1910", "dates": ["[1910 TO 9999]"], "description": ["Daily, Feb. 13, 1911- Print began with December 1, 1910. Published in multiple editions. Spanish language eds.: Miami herald (Miami, Fla. : 1976), 1976-1987, and: Nuevo herald, 1987- Vol. I, no. 28 (January 1, 1911); title from masthead, Readex PDF (viewed April 28, 2020) April 27, 2020; Readex, viewed April 28, 2020."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-05-19T21:37:48.715Z", "group": ["ndnp/newspapers", "catalog-split-13", "catalog", "united-states-newspaper-directory", "main-catalog-split-13"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/2019201725/", "image_url": [], "index": 11, "language": ["english"], "location": ["dade county", "miami", "united states", "florida", "dade"], "number": ["2019201720", "online resource", "1117775814", "2025-11-07t12:23:46.500000", "2688-8920", "2019201725", "2026-04-13t21:30:13"], "original_format": ["newspaper"], "other_title": ["Some providers have title: Miami herald historical and current"], "partof": ["miami herald (miami, fla.;miami fl) 1910-current [online resource]", "catalog", "directory of u.s. newspapers in american libraries", "serial and government publications division"], "publication_frequency": ["daily"], "score": 66.383484, "shelf_id": "Newspaper", "site": ["usnd", "catalog"], "subject": ["dade", "newspapers", "miami-dade county", "miami-dade county (fla.)", "periodicals", "miami", "electronic journals", "united states", "florida", "miami (fla.)"], "timestamp": "2026-05-26T20:57:39.303Z", "title": "Miami herald", "type": ["title"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/2019201725/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/item/sn82001257/", "http://lccn.loc.gov/sn82001257", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/b2d21f67-4dd9-5333-84e8-687bf3203ed1"], "batch": ["fu_anastasia_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "date": "1953", "description": ["The Diario las Ame\u0301ricas (sn82001257), published by the Ame\u0301ricas Pub. Co., began printing in November 1953 as a member of the Inter-American Press Association. It published an issue daily (except for on Mondays), primarily in Spanish \"por la libertad, la cultura y la solidaridad hemisferica\" (for liberty, culture, and hemispheric solidarity). The Diario was published in Miami, which was founded in the 1890s by Julia Tuttle, the only (white) woman to found a major city in the United States. Since its early days, the city served as the home base for many Hispanics fleeing their mother nations due to economic and political hardships. A case in point is the exodus of Cubans to Miami after Fidel Castro claimed power in Cuba in 1959. While Cubans make up the majority of the city's population, Miami is home to newcomers from Colombia, the Dominican Republic, Haiti, Honduras, Nicaragua, and other Latin American/Caribbean nations. From its inception issues of the Diario were published in Spanish, except for the very last page of every issue which was printed in English. This \"Inter-American News for English-speaking people\" section was a dedicated space to share news and reach the English-speaking community. However, in August 1958, the publisher altered the publication by removing this English-language \"Inter-American News\" section and replaced it with a \"Noticias de Miami y Florida\" (news from Miami and Florida) to further serve its Spanish-speaking community. It also included a recurring section \"La Voz de Tampa\" (The Voice of Tampa), which featured news directly from the paper's Tampa office. During the 1950s and 1960s, the Diario provided local news coverage, its primary concern seemed to be connecting with the international community and providing news from abroad. It offered a recurring section \"Iberoamerica al d\u00eda\" (daily Iberian America) that published accounts of events occurring all over Latin America and the Caribbean. The paper also offered sections covering happenings in Cuba, Puerto Rico, and Colombia. It informed its readers of the events leading up to the Cuban Revolution in 1959. It also documented discussions around the Commonwealth status of Puerto Rico and reported on political and social challenges leading to guerilla movements in Colombia. Additionally, the Diario included supplemental material for several years. \"Hemisferio\" (Hemisphere) was an affiliated magazine that published an issue every week during the first few years of publication. Like the traditional issues of the newspaper, the Hemisferio was printed primarily in Spanish, typically offering one page of content printed in English. It offered readers varying stories from Florida, the Caribbean, and Latin America. For example, readers can learn about the development of Miami, Las Ferias de Manizales (the largest and most symbolic celebration of the city of Manizales Colombia), and Bosquejos (sketches) of countries like Haiti that offer a glimpse into the life of residents of the featured nation."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-06-05T18:25:17.113Z", "group": ["newspaper-titles", "ndnp/newspapers", "catalog-split-10", "catalog", "united-states-newspaper-directory", "main-catalog-split-10"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/sn82001257/", "image_url": [], "index": 12, "language": ["english", "spanish"], "latlong": [25.775084, -80.194702], "location": ["dade county", "miami", "miami-dade", "miami springs", "united states", "florida", "dade"], "location_str": "", "lonlat": [-80.194702, 25.775084], "number": ["microfilm master", "http://www.loc.gov/item/sn82001257/1953-11-26/ed-1/", "online resource", "center for res libr, newsp proj", "sn82001257", "0744-3234", "1", "microfilm service copy", "1774712", "original", "2175", "univ of texas at austin", "2025-05-23t21:30:26", "2025-11-07t12:28:07.700000", "library of congress", "http://www.loc.gov/item/sn82001257/1963-12-31/ed-1/", "2026-04-13t21:30:13"], "original_format": ["newspaper"], "other_title": ["Americas daily"], "partof": ["catalog", "chronicling america", "serial and government publications division", "di